<taxonomicName authority="(Muir)" authorityName="Zelazny" authorityYear="1981" baseAuthorityName="Muir" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[329,573,1543,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Alara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis box="[329,490,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Alara obscura</emphasis>
(Muir)
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Zelazny &amp; Webb, 2011" authorityName="Zelazny &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2011" box="[722,861,1544,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Alara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aquilonia" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[722,861,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">A. aquilonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[869,957,1544,1567]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1026,1083,1544,1567]" name="Laos" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Laos</collectingCountry>
, but has the bases of the dorsal processes on the male genital styles nearly merging and a longer aedeagus with the apical portion widening towards its end.
</paragraph>
